english:
  title: Sending Off Choe Hama, Inspector of Gyeongsang Province
  author: Go Jungji
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Geumjung Mountain rises high, so very high—
    Its rocky peaks rival even Heaven's Eye.
    Below spreads Dongnae Castle,
    Where mist and rosy clouds nest in ancient trees.

    The world calls this the dwelling of immortals,
    Where earth runs clear and spirits dwell refined.
    Even at noon the clouds breathe down their vapor,
    While hot springs surge through mountain hollows.

    Travelers rest beside these waters,
    And bathe in warmth through winter's bitter cold.
    Wild bridges press upon the tranquil lake,
    Small pavilions lean against the broken ridge.

    Once the immortal Suhan came here,
    Riding white deer through these very trails.
    Who built that guest pavilion? No one knows—
    Yet its grandeur stands unmatched beneath heaven.

    The northern hall bears the name “Emerald Gathering,”
    Where a thousand stalks of jade bamboo sway.
    On moonlit nights the plum branches freeze,
    While autumn winds ripen oranges and pomelos.

    Gaze eastward toward the lonely Cloud Platform—
    Crimson peaks pierce the sea, sharp and proud.
    Even a brief sojourn in this place
    Will fill a lifetime's heart with sufficiency.

    I am a child of these mountains,
    Where the great river winds past my thatched door.
    In vain I chased the path of fame and office,
    Floundering through dust and earthly toil.

    Yet even now, in dreams that return,
    I hear the song of the Canglan Stream, calling me back.
    Now I send you forth as the imperial messenger—
    Guard for me the pine and chrysanthemum still growing there.
  footnotes:
    - Geumjung Mountain (금정산) is located in present-day Busan, Korea, known for its spiritual significance and natural beauty.
    - Heaven's Eye (천목산, Tianmu Mountain) is a sacred mountain in China, referenced here as a point of comparison for natural grandeur.
    - Suhan (소하, Su He or Suhe) refers to a legendary immortal from Chinese tradition believed to have visited sacred Korean mountains.
    - The Canglan Stream (창랑, Canglan) is referenced from the famous 'Fisherman's Song' (Canglangge), symbolizing retreat from worldly affairs into nature.
    - The imperial messenger reference (황화) alludes to the sending off of officials on government duty, following classical Chinese protocol.
